            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.IX.R2</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Pursue Rigaud [...]</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Dickens&rsquo;s instructions to himself (&ldquo;Suspend it all. Hanging Sword&rdquo;) indicate his awareness that this scene is preparatory for Book II and the downfall of the house. It is in this interaction between Rigaud and Mrs. Clennam (with Jeremiah and Affery present) in which Rigaud (as Blandois) notices the watch, and where we first hear of the inscription: D. N. F.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This number features a series of &ldquo;suspended&rdquo; plots, suggestions of future revelations that deepen the mystery. Along with the hint here of Rigaud&rsquo;s future threat to the Clennam house, the Notes for this number suggest and &ldquo;suspend&rdquo; Pancks&rsquo;s discovery, the possibility of the Dorrits behaving differently in a &ldquo;higher station,&rdquo; and even the possibility of the Little Dorrit-Arthur Clennam union.&nbsp;</p>"
        }
    ],
